      "source": [
        "# 1: What is Simple Linear Regression?\n",
        "\n",
        "Answer:\n",
        "Simple Linear Regression is a statistical technique that models the relationship between a dependent variable and one independent variable using a straight line (y = mx + b). It aims to find the best-fitting line that predicts the dependent variable based on the independent variable."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "3w0u-zp28cJT"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "2: What are the key assumptions of Simple Linear Regression?\n",
        "\n",
        "Answer:\n",
        "\n",
        "1. Linearity – The relationship between X and Y is linear.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "2. Independence – Observations are independent of each other.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "3. Homoscedasticity – Constant variance of residuals.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "4. Normality – Residuals should be normally distributed.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "5. No multicollinearity (mainly applies in multiple regression).#"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "g1iIbi_O8mqq"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "# 3: What is heteroscedasticity, and why is it important to address in regression models?\n",
        "\n",
        "Answer:\n",
        "Heteroscedasticity refers to the unequal spread of residuals (errors) across the values of the independent variable(s). It violates the assumption of constant variance and can lead to inefficient estimates and unreliable hypothesis testing in regression models."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "mcuIN_rS823R"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "# 4: What is Multiple Linear Regression?\n",
        "\n",
        "Answer:\n",
        "Multiple Linear Regression is a method that models the relationship between one dependent variable and two or more independent variables. The equation used is:\n",
        "Y = b0 + b1X1 + b2X2 + ... + bnXn"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "iMMHibKW86EM"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "# 5: What is polynomial regression, and how does it differ from linear regression?\n",
        "\n",
        "Answer:\n",
        "Polynomial regression is a form of regression that models the relationship between the dependent variable and independent variable as an nth-degree polynomial. Unlike linear regression (which fits a straight line), polynomial regression can fit curves and capture more complex patterns in the data."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "bxIi05n_89dd"
      }
    },

      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "## Question 6: Fit a Simple Linear Regression model and plot the regression line\n",
        "\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "\n",
        "# Sample Data\n",
        "X = np.array([1, 2, 3, 4, 5]).reshape(-1, 1)\n",
        "Y = np.array([2.1, 4.3, 6.1, 7.9, 10.2])\n",
        "\n",
        "# Create and fit the model\n",
        "model = LinearRegression()\n",
        "model.fit(X, Y)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Predict Y values\n",
        "Y_pred = model.predict(X)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Plotting\n",
        "plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))\n",
        "plt.scatter(X, Y, color='blue', label='Actual Data')\n",
        "plt.plot(X, Y_pred, color='red', label='Regression Line')\n",
        "plt.title('Simple Linear Regression')\n",
        "plt.xlabel('X')\n",
        "plt.ylabel('Y')\n",
        "plt.legend()\n",
        "plt.grid(True)\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ],

        "import pandas as pd\n",
        "from statsmodels.stats.outliers_influence import variance_inflation_factor\n",
        "from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression\n",
        "\n",
        "# Data\n",
        "data = pd.DataFrame({\n",
        "    'Area': [1200, 1500, 1800, 2000],\n",
        "    'Rooms': [2, 3, 3, 4],\n",
        "    'Price': [250000, 300000, 320000, 370000]\n",
        "})\n",
        "\n",
        "# Features and Target\n",
        "X = data[['Area', 'Rooms']]\n",
        "y = data['Price']\n",
        "\n",
        "# VIF Calculation\n",
        "vif_data = pd.DataFrame()\n",
        "vif_data['feature'] = X.columns\n",
        "vif_data['VIF'] = [variance_inflation_factor(X.values, i) for i in range(X.shape[1])]\n",
        "\n",
        "# Model fitting\n",
        "model = LinearRegression()\n",
        "model.fit(X, y)\n",
        "\n",
        "print(\"✅ Multiple Linear Regression Coefficients:\")\n",
        "print(\"Intercept:\", model.intercept_)\n",
        "print(\"Coefficients:\", model.coef_)\n",
        "print(\"\\n📌 Variance Inflation Factors (VIF):\")\n",
        "print(vif_data)"
      ],

        "import numpy as np\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "from sklearn.preprocessing import PolynomialFeatures\n",
        "from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression\n",
        "\n",
        "# Data\n",
        "X = np.array([1, 2, 3, 4, 5]).reshape(-1, 1)\n",
        "Y = np.array([2.2, 4.8, 7.5, 11.2, 14.7])\n",
        "\n",
        "# Polynomial transformation (degree = 2)\n",
        "poly = PolynomialFeatures(degree=2)\n",
        "X_poly = poly.fit_transform(X)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Model training\n",
        "model = LinearRegression()\n",
        "model.fit(X_poly, Y)\n",
        "Y_pred = model.predict(X_poly)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Plotting\n",
        "plt.figure()\n",
        "plt.scatter(X, Y, color='blue', label='Data')\n",
        "plt.plot(X, Y_pred, color='green', label='Polynomial Fit')\n",
        "plt.xlabel('X')\n",
        "plt.ylabel('Y')\n",
        "plt.title('Polynomial Regression')\n",
        "plt.legend()\n",
        "plt.grid(True)\n",
        "plt.show()\n",
        "\n",
        "print(\"✅ Polynomial Regression (degree=2) completed.\")\n",
        "print(\"Intercept:\", model.intercept_)\n",
        "print(\"Coefficients:\", model.coef_)"
      ],

        "# Data\n",
        "X = np.array([10, 20, 30, 40, 50]).reshape(-1, 1)\n",
        "Y = np.array([15, 35, 40, 50, 65])\n",
        "\n",
        "# Model fitting\n",
        "model = LinearRegression()\n",
        "model.fit(X, Y)\n",
        "Y_pred = model.predict(X)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Residuals\n",
        "residuals = Y - Y_pred\n",
        "\n",
        "# Residual plot\n",
        "plt.figure()\n",
        "plt.scatter(X, residuals)\n",
        "plt.axhline(y=0, color='red', linestyle='--')\n",
        "plt.xlabel('X')\n",
        "plt.ylabel('Residuals')\n",
        "plt.title('Residuals Plot')\n",
        "plt.grid(True)\n",
        "plt.show()\n",
        "\n",
        "print(\"✅ Residuals plotted to check for heteroscedasticity.\")"
